<br>
Besides that, 90% of the bad pathing in the game comes from circular pathing.  You know what Im talking about...  Floor 5 of Tower of Frozen Shadow is a circle, theres a circle around the well near the Soothsayer in Droga, there is circular pathing around each house in Hate.<br>
<br>
The way its coded is, rather than take the path with the closest distance, circular pathing is one way...like blocks in New York City.  Pets and mobs only go one way around the circle.  Most of the zone in wipeouts in hate are caused by the fact that an enemy notices you from behind the nearby wall where you enter.  They cant just run to the doorway to enter the entry building by taking the shortest route...instead they go all the way around multiple buildings and back (around a one way circle), causing more enemies to come as well.  In Plane of Hate when you tell your pet to attack something and see your pet spastically take off down away from you and then back around in a circle towards the enemy, it's because of the same phenomenon. One way circular pathing.  For some reason, this pathing is placed all over in Hate in places it does not belong.<br>
<br>
So anyways, thats how you can predict bad pathing. Look for places with circles. If you see one, dont summon a pet unless the entire circle is safe for the pet to move about in.<br>
<br>
As to the other 10%, it usually takes place in areas where pathing is missing.  Pets will hop skip and jump around because they cant find the right path to their master or the enemy they want to fight.  For example, in skyshrine, if you summon a pet in the area after you step  on the first teleporter pad (at wyverns), and walk up the ramp walkway, the pet will ridiculously warp down to the courtyard. Fun. <p><img src="http://www.lehigh.edu/~dsf3/EQ/rhionsligo.jpg" align="center">
